    <grammar_table id="classical" title="classical">
        <description>-o- becomes -u- before final consonants (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 66), nominative/vocative -ros/-re becomes -r after vowels and -er after consonants (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 70), vocative -ie and genitive -iī become -ī (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 256, 260), dative -ōi and ablative -ōd become -ō (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 58, 228), word-final -ns becomes -s with lengthening of preceding vocal (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 215), -ā becomes -a (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 78), introduction of singular genitive in -ī (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 260), -ois becomes -eis becomes -īs (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 263), same with -āis (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 272), o-stem genitive plural partly modeled after a-stem (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 264), o-stem nominative plural is replaced from the pronoun -oi becoming -ei becoming -ī (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 260), same with a-stem nominative plural (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 271), long vowels before -m got short (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 78), -āi shortened to -ae (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 268), loss of word-final -d after a long vowel (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 228), in a-stem plural dative-ablative –īs is replaced with -ābus where necessary to avoid homophony with o-stem plural dative-ablatives (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 272), intervocalic -s becomes -r (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 171-172). A locative plural in -īs is too speculative (<source book="Sihler" /> p. 253 only mentions it, prefixed with a "perhaps") to include in the table.</description>
        <declension_def id="sg" short_title="singular">
